description.narrative: 1. Screening, hit-to-lead. 2. Together with partners at the Drug Discovery Unit and Wellcome Trust Centre for Anti-Infectives Research at the University of Dundee (DDU), pharmaceutical companies GlaxoSmithKline (GSK), Pfizer, Takeda, and Celgene, and the product development partnership TB Alliance, DNDi has built an unprecedented portfolio of lead series, pre-clinical, and clinical candidates for leishmaniasis. DNDi will work to advance this unique portfolio, with the goal of progressing drug candidates through Phase I clinical development, and for the most promising clinical candidates to be selected for a Phase II clinical trial testing the safety and efficacy of a combination of two entirely new chemical entities. 3. Cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL): demonstrate the suitability of an immunomodulator to stimulate the innate immune system to fight the parasitic infection responsible for CL and explore whether a combination of thermotherapy with a shorter course of oral miltefosine achieves better results than thermotherapy alone. 4. New treatments for HIV/visceral leishmaniasis (VL): identify and deliver a safe and highly effective treatment for VL in HIV co-infected patients that will improve their long-term survival. 5. Post-kala-azar dermal leishmaniasis (PKDL): determine the safety and efficacy of treatment regimens for people with PKDL in East Africa and South Asia, and understand the role of PKDL in VL transmission. 6. Compare the efficacy and safety of two combinations regimens of miltefosine and paromomycin with the current standard treatment 7. New VL treatments in Latin America. 8. DNDi continues to accompany the implementation of SSG+PM in East Africa, as well as of new treatment options for VL in South Asia.

DNDi aims to make treatments safer, shorter, and more affordable and effective for all forms of leishmaniasis. In the short term, better treatment regiments are being developed using existing drugs. In the long term the goal is to develop an entirely new generation of all-oral drugs.
